  <PNotes>
    When a user activates High Contrast Mode, the browser takes full control of
    the color palette. It stops using the colors defined in your CSS and
    switches everything to the system's own high-contrast colors.<br /><br /> We
    don't get to enforce our brand colors anymore, but we can request exceptions.
    With forced-color-adjust, we can say: "Keep this specific element as I designed
    it, but feel free to recolor everything else." <br /><br />It's one of the
    few situations where CSS becomes diplomatic rather than directive
  </PNotes>
